metadata.title: Piper PA-28 Cherokee
aws::graph::propositions: # Piper PA-28 Cherokee Archer Family Models
The Archer family is part of the Piper PA-28 Cherokee aircraft line.
The PA-28-180 Challenger is a four-place aircraft.
The PA-28-180 Challenger has fixed landing gear.
The PA-28-180 Challenger is classified as a landplane.
The PA-28-180 Challenger is powered by a Lycoming O-360-A4A engine or a Lycoming O-360-A4M engine.
The Lycoming O-360-A4A engine produces 180 hp (134 kW).
The Lycoming O-360-A4M engine produces 180 hp (134 kW).
The PA-28-180 Challenger has a gross weight of 2,450 lb (1,111 kg).
The PA-28-180 Challenger was first certified on May 22, 1972.
The PA-28-180 Challenger features a five inch fuselage extension compared to the PA-28-180 Cherokee.
The PA-28-180 Challenger features increased wing span compared to the PA-28-180 Cherokee.
The PA-28-180 Challenger features a larger horizontal tail compared to the PA-28-180 Cherokee.
The PA-28-180 Challenger features increased gross weight compared to the PA-28-180 Cherokee.
The PA-28-180 Challenger was renamed to Archer after minor detail changes.
The PA-28-181 Archer II is a four-place aircraft.
The PA-28-181 Archer II has fixed landing gear.
The PA-28-181 Archer II is classified as a landplane.
The PA-28-181 Archer II is powered by a Lycoming O-360-A4A engine or a Lycoming O-360-A4M engine.
The PA-28-181 Archer II's Lycoming O-360-A4A engine produces 180 hp (134 kW).
The PA-28-181 Archer II's Lycoming O-360-A4M engine produces 180 hp (134 kW).
The PA-28-181 Archer II has a gross weight of 2,550 lb (1,157 kg).
The PA-28-181 Archer II was first certified on July 8, 1975.
The PA-28-181 Archer II features a tapered wing compared to the PA-28-180 Archer.

text:
### Archer family
PA-28-180 Challenger
Four-place, fixed landing gear landplane, Lycoming O-360-A4A or -A4M engine of 180 hp (134 kW), gross weight 2,450 lb (1,111 kg). First certified on May 22, 1972. Changes from the PA-28-180 Cherokee include a five inch fuselage extension, wing span increase, larger horizontal tail, gross weight increase and other minor changes.  Renamed to Archer after minor detail changes.
PA-28-181 Archer II
Four-place, fixed landing gear landplane, Lycoming O-360-A4A or -A4M engine of 180 hp (134 kW), gross weight 2,550 lb (1,157 kg). First certified on July 8, 1975. Changes from the PA-28-180 Archer include a tapered wing.
